A small data team running pro bono analytics for a regional nonprofit network has half a dozen volunteer data scientists collaborating on modeling projects: predicting which donors are likely to lapse, which volunteers will return, which program participants are at risk of falling out. Members have different backgrounds and the team needs a coordination app for collaborative modeling work since current GitHub-plus-Slack workflow does not capture modeling decisions well. Build a community modeling workspace where each project gets a shared page that records the problem framing (classification of lapse risk, e.g.), the candidate datasets the team has access to, and the modeling decisions being explored. Team members can each propose a modeling approach — one volunteer might try logistic regression with careful feature engineering, another decision trees and random forests, a third support vector machines, a fourth a small neural network — and the workspace shows the cross-validation results from each, with each member's notes on what they tried for regularization, model selection, and feature choices. The team should be able to discuss tradeoffs in threaded comments tied to specific decisions: 'Why principal component analysis here? Wouldn't that lose interpretability the program director needs?' For clustering analyses (segmenting donors by behavior, segmenting volunteers by engagement pattern), members can propose alternative clustering algorithms and discuss the resulting segments together. The team lead can promote a leading approach to 'recommended' and tag the project as ready for handoff to the nonprofit, with a written non-technical summary the team drafts collaboratively. Over time the workspace builds the team's institutional memory: which approaches worked for which kinds of nonprofit problems, what feature engineering matters most in this domain, and which volunteers have which strengths.